:: Ending {"position":"1150,150","size":"100,100"}
{(set: $ethicscore to ($trust + $wb))
(set: $growthscore to ($eng + $rev))}

<div class="endwrap">

{(if: $ethicscore >= 160)[
<div class="endtitle">The Ethical Pivot</div>
<span class="endtag taggood">// Outcome: Low Growth &mdash; High Integrity</span>

<p>The investor demo is a quiet disaster. You present real numbers. Engagement is down, revenue projections revised, the growth curve flattened. You explain why. Two investors leave early. One stays late.</p>

<p>She asks to speak privately. She says she has seen this pattern before &mdash; companies that make the hard calls early tend to survive what comes next. She does not offer a term sheet. She offers a second meeting in three months.</p>

<p>Asante's report runs in <em>The Atlantic</em> six weeks later. A Congressional subcommittee cites Nexus by name &mdash; not as a villain, but as a company that documented its own ethical deliberations and eventually made different choices. A Stanford ethics course assigns the case study. Your name appears in the footnotes.</p>

<p>Nexus does not collapse. It rebuilds slowly, with a smaller team and a different set of metrics on the dashboard. You do not know yet whether this was the right call. You know you made it with your eyes open.</p>

<div class="rsrc"><span class="rtag">Research Context &mdash; Zuboff (2019)</span>Zuboff argues surveillance capitalism's deepest problem is not any individual product decision, but the normalization of behavioral extraction as a business model. This path does not solve that structural problem. It refuses to participate in it &mdash; at real cost. The distinction, she would argue, still matters.</div>

](else-if: $growthscore >= 160)[
<div class="endtitle">The Unicorn</div>
<span class="endtag tagbad">// Outcome: High Growth &mdash; Contested Ethics</span>

<p>The demo goes extremely well. Your numbers impress. Engagement up, session times climbing, revenue on an aggressive curve. The lead investor calls it "one of the cleaner pitches" of the cycle. The term sheet arrives before the weekend.</p>

<p>Seven months later, Asante's document surfaces through a FOIA request on a regulatory filing your legal team filed and forgot about. The story that runs is less about what Nexus did and more about what it knew, and when, and who knew it.</p>

<p>Your decisions are reconstructed in a <em>Washington Post</em> piece. The internal emails are quoted. The word "vulnerabilities" appears in the headline. You are given the option to resign or be let go. The framing, your lawyer says, is up to you.</p>

<p>Nexus survives. You probably do too. But there is a version of this story where you made these same calls without knowing what you knew &mdash; and another version where you knew, and chose differently. You are living in the one where you knew.</p>

<div class="rsrc"><span class="rtag">Research Context &mdash; K.G.M. v. Meta et al. (2026)</span>The central legal argument is not that platforms caused harm by accident &mdash; it is that they had internal documentation showing harm and continued the practices anyway. The question is not capability. It is awareness and choice. Both of those were present here.</div>

][
<div class="endtitle">The Compromise</div>
<span class="endtag tagmid">// Outcome: Unstable Equilibrium</span>

<p>The demo is fine. Not a triumph, not a failure. Careful questions. Careful answers. The term sheet comes with conditions: a 90-day performance review tied to engagement benchmarks. Three months to show the trajectory they are betting on.</p>

<p>Asante stays. He keeps the document private, for now. Everyone goes back to work. The system runs. Users scroll. The metrics update. Nothing is resolved &mdash; it is deferred, reconfigured, held in a tension that feels stable until it does not.</p>

<p>You check your own phone more than you used to. You notice the feeling the feed produces &mdash; a low-grade urgency that is not quite satisfaction and not quite need. You know exactly how it works. You helped decide how it works. That knowledge does not make it easier to put down. If anything, it makes it harder.</p>

<div class="rsrc"><span class="rtag">Research Context &mdash; Narayanan et al. (2020) and Susser et al. (2019)</span>The most effective behavioral design is often invisible not because it actively deceives, but because the environment is structured to make certain choices easier and others harder. The compromise is not neutral. The feed is still running. It is still learning. It is learning right now.</div>
]}

