## Sources That Shaped This Project

<div class="term"><span class="tlabel">// Research Integration</span>Zuboff, S. (2019). The Age of Surveillance Capitalism. PublicAffairs.
  &rarr; Behavioral surplus logic; the inherited system Jordan manages

Narayanan, A., Mathur, A., Chetty, M., and Kshirsagar, M. (2020).
  Dark Patterns: Past, Present, and Future. ACM Queue, 18(2).
  &rarr; Consent architecture; opt-out design; obstructing transparency

Susser, D., Roessler, B., and Nissenbaum, H. (2019).
  Online Manipulation: Hidden Influences in a Digital World.
  Ethics and Information Technology, 21(1), 1-13.
  &rarr; Persuasion vs. manipulation; rational agency; the algorithm gradient

Gonzalez v. Google LLC, 598 U.S. 617 (2023).
  &rarr; Recommendation algorithm accountability; Section 230 limits

K.G.M. v. Meta Platforms et al. (2026).
  &rarr; Addictive design; known harm documentation; disclosure obligations</div>

<hr class="divider">

<div class="term"><span class="tlabel">// Design Note</span>This project was conceived, researched, written, and built by Myles Scott.
All ethical framing, narrative structure, character design, game mechanics,
metric logic, and ending outcomes were developed by the author.
Research integration was deliberate: each source shapes a specific round,
not merely the surface content.

The Twine format was chosen because an essay can describe these tradeoffs.
Only a simulation can make you feel the weight of choosing between them &mdash;
and the discomfort of recognizing, at the end, that the system you just ran
is the same one running on your phone right now.</div>

