## You went opt-in only.

Only 29% of users explicitly consent to behavioral tracking. The feed becomes less "accurate." It also, depending on your definitions, becomes less manipulative.

<p>A tech ethics newsletter runs a short piece: "Nexus just did what no major platform has done." A digital rights researcher tweets it. Dana has forwarded the tweet to the exec team with the subject line: "Context needed."</p>

<p>The question that follows you is whether a less personalized feed is genuinely better for users, or whether you have simply made the system less useful and are calling it ethics. You are not sure you know the answer yet.</p>

<div class="rsrc"><span class="rtag">Research Context &mdash; Gonzalez v. Google (2023)</span>The case raised &mdash; but did not resolve &mdash; whether algorithmic recommendation systems bear responsibility for the content they amplify. Moving to opt-in narrows the data Nexus uses, but does not eliminate the underlying accountability gap in what gets recommended to the users who do consent.</div>

