## You surfaced the opt-out.

One tap. Plain language. "Stop tracking my cursor and deleted searches." Ships in a Tuesday update.

<p>Within 48 hours, 14% of users opt out. That is larger than anyone expected, which means something: people wanted this option and never had it. Priya sends a note saying it is the right call. Dana sends nothing.</p>

<p>Personalization accuracy drops slightly for opted-out users. The system learns less about them, which means it can influence them less. Whether that is a bug or a feature, you realize, depends entirely on what you think the system is for.</p>

<div class="rsrc"><span class="rtag">Research Context &mdash; Susser, Roessler and Nissenbaum (2019)</span>The authors distinguish manipulation from persuasion by asking whether influence operates on or around a person's rational agency. Surfacing the opt-out restores some of that agency &mdash; but only for users who notice it and use it. The structural imbalance of knowledge remains.</div>

<div class="db">
<div class="dbtitle">// Nexus Live Metrics</div>
<div class="mr"><div class="ml"><span class="mn">Engagement</span><span class="mv">(if: $eng > 100)[100](else-if: $eng < 0)[0](else:)[$eng]</span></div><div class="mb"><div class="mf fe" style="width:(if: $eng > 100)[100](else-if: $eng < 0)[0](else:)[$eng]%"></div></div></div>
