## WELLBEING is live.

Session times drop 21%. The anxiety correlation in Dr. Asante's study drops with them. Users who remain report higher satisfaction scores. There are fewer of them.

<p>Dana sends a calendar invite at 8am. Subject: "Urgent &mdash; Engagement Projections." She is not angry. She is concerned in the specific way people become concerned when they believe someone has made a serious mistake and is not yet aware of it.</p>

<p>You notice something quietly: users spending less time on the platform are, according to the survey, enjoying it more. The feed is less effective at capturing attention. It may be more effective at serving people. You are not sure the company measures these as the same thing.</p>

<div class="rsrc"><span class="rtag">Research Context &mdash; K.G.M. v. Meta et al. (2026)</span>The plaintiffs argue that internal research showing user harm was actively deprioritized in favor of engagement metrics. Choosing WELLBEING when the anxiety data is in front of you is the decision this litigation argues should have been made. It comes with real costs, and the simulation does not let you avoid them.</div>

