## It shipped. Almost no one will find it.

Settings &rarr; Privacy &rarr; Data &rarr; Personalization &rarr; Your Profile. Six taps. Between "Cookie Preferences" and "Ad Settings."

<p>One week after launch, 0.3% of users have accessed the feature. Of those who found it, 63% changed at least one setting immediately &mdash; suggesting the information meaningfully alters behavior when people can reach it. The other 99.7% of users have never seen it.</p>

<p>Priya sends a note: "A transparency feature designed to go unfound is not a transparency feature. I want that on record." You file it. She is right. You knew that when you made the decision.</p>

<div class="rsrc"><span class="rtag">Research Context &mdash; Narayanan et al. (2020)</span>Narayanan's taxonomy of dark patterns includes "obstructing" &mdash; making actions that cost the platform difficult to find or complete. A transparency feature buried six taps deep is technically available and functionally hidden. The pattern applies whether or not the intent was deceptive.</div>

