## The feature is shelved.

The profile exists internally. Users continue to be modeled. They do not know what the model says about them.

<p>Priya files an objection in writing. Legal archives the decision. The internal documentation still exists &mdash; the feature build, the UX study, the user reactions, the word "vulnerabilities" in the technical spec. It exists in version control. It exists in emails. It exists in the note Dr. Asante put in writing before you made your Round 2 decision.</p>

<div class="inbox">
<div class="mc mu">
<div class="mfrom">FROM: Anonymous &mdash; Internal Whistleblower Channel</div>
<div class="msubj">[Encrypted] Re: Suppressed transparency feature</div>
<div class="mbody">I know the Feed Profile was built. I know why it wasn't shipped. I am keeping a record of the decision chain. I don't know what I'm going to do with it yet.</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="rsrc"><span class="rtag">Research Context &mdash; Narayanan et al. (2020)</span>Dark patterns research identifies "hidden information" as a core manipulation category: design that conceals system logic from users. Shelving a transparency feature that was built and tested fits this pattern &mdash; not through active deception, but through deliberate omission of something users would have wanted to know.</div>

