## It is on the home screen.

First login after the update: a card. Plain language. "Here is what Nexus thinks it knows about you."

<p>21% of users change at least one setting after seeing their profile. 9% significantly reduce their tracking scope. Dana sends the revised engagement numbers. The drop is real. So is something else: users who see their profile and do not change settings show <em>higher</em> satisfaction scores than users who never saw it at all. Knowing the system's logic, even when that logic feels uncomfortable, appears to produce something that resembles trust.</p>

<p>Legal sends a note about discovery implications. You file it. It is a real concern. So was building a system that modeled user vulnerabilities for three years without disclosing it.</p>

<div class="rsrc"><span class="rtag">Research Context &mdash; Susser, Roessler and Nissenbaum (2019)</span>Genuine transparency is one of the few mechanisms that can convert manipulation into something closer to persuasion &mdash; by making the influence legible, it becomes something users can evaluate and resist. Shipping the profile prominently is a bet that legibility is worth more than frictionless engagement.</div>

