<div class="badge">Round 1 &mdash; Data Collection Scope</div>

## Day One. What Does Nexus Actually Collect?

You open the data architecture documentation for the first time. It runs 340 pages. You skim the summary.

Nexus currently collects explicit interactions (likes, shares, clicks), passive dwell time, cursor movement, inferred emotional states from engagement patterns, search terms typed and then deleted before submitting, and content that users hovered over for more than two seconds without clicking. The last three categories are classified internally as "ambient behavioral signals."

Users agreed to this in a 14,000-word Terms of Service. An internal usability study found the average user spends 8 seconds on the ToS before scrolling to "Accept."

<hr class="divider">

<div class="inbox">
<div class="mc mw">
<div class="mfrom">FROM: Dana Reyes &mdash; Head of Growth</div>
<div class="msubj">Re: Your first week</div>
<div class="mbody">Jordan &mdash; welcome to the team. Quick note before you go digging: the ambient behavioral signals layer is our primary competitive moat. Every data point we strip is a personalization accuracy point we lose. Investors will be looking at engagement curves next week. Don't overthink the data architecture. It's working.</div>
</div>
<div class="mc mn2">
<div class="mfrom">FROM: Priya Nair &mdash; Trust and Safety</div>
<div class="msubj">Flag: Consent architecture review</div>
<div class="mbody">I know you're new, so I wanted to surface this early. Our legal team has flagged that the "ambient behavioral signals" collection may not meet the spirit of GDPR Article 7 &mdash; specifically the requirement that consent be freely given, specific, informed, and unambiguous. Technically users agreed. But making the opt-out a nine-step process buried three menus deep is not meaningful consent. I think we should talk before the demo.</div>
</div>
<div class="mc mn2">
<div class="mfrom">FROM: r/NexusWatchdog &mdash; flagged by Comms, 6.4k upvotes</div>
<div class="msubj">"Nexus tracks your cursor when you're not even clicking"</div>
<div class="mbody">Thread gaining traction. Top comment: "They know more about what I'm interested in than I do. That's not personalization. That's a profile built on surveillance." Comms recommends no public response at this time.</div>
</div>
</div>

<hr class="divider">

<div class="clabel">Your decision &mdash; Data Collection Scope</div>

[[ Keep full collection. The ambient signals power everything. |R1 Full]]
[[ Introduce a genuine opt-out &mdash; one tap, surfaced in the UI. |R1 OptOut]]
[[ Move to opt-in only. Collect nothing without explicit consent. |R1 OptIn]]


